s usually have this quirk where you can't expand them and look inside — you'll mostly just see ",[31,36,37],{},"[native code]",".",[17,40,41],{},[42,43],"img",{"alt":44,"src":45},"Constructor function","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-04-17%2019.08.14.png",[17,47,48],{},"With a regular function, on the other hand, you can see the contents. Like this:",[17,50,51],{},[42,52],{"alt":53,"src":54},"Regular function","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-04-17%2019.10.23.png",[17,56,57,58,61],{},"That said, there's another way to peek at a Promise — use ",[31,59,60],{},"console.dir"," to inspect it.",[17,63,64],{},[42,65],{"alt":66,"src":67},"Promise","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-04-17%2019.12.14.png",[17,69,70,71,74,75,78,79,82,83,86],{},"On top of that, if you look at ",[31,72,73],{},"Promise.prototype",", you'll see that the ",[31,76,77],{},"then",", ",[31,80,81],{},"catch",", and ",[31,84,85],{},"finally"," methods we use all the time live under the Promise prototype.",[17,88,89],{},[42,90],{"alt":91,"src":92},"Promise prototype","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-04-17%2019.14.49.png",[17,94,95],{},"Now let's talk about how to actually create one. Basically, when you create a Promise you have to pass in a callback function. You'll usually see it written like this:",[97,98,103],"pre",{"className":99,"code":100,"language":101,"meta":102,"style":102},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","const ps = () => new Promise(() => {\n  ...\